# Backend service contracts

## Shape (orchestrators under `**/services/**`)

- **`@dataclass` service** with dependencies as fields (often `_leading_underscore` for collaborators).
- **Wiring:** single `@classmethod def build(cls) -> Self` constructs DAOs/clients/nested services. Non-test call sites prefer `Service.build()`.
- **Single public work method:** `def execute(self, ...) -> ...` — no extra public “do” methods on the same orchestrator.
- **One concrete use-case per service** — if the class name is `CreateXService`, `execute` only creates `X` for that flow; split unrelated flows into separate services.

## `execute` parameters

- **No “request bag” DTO** that only bundles unrelated caller fields — unpack explicit arguments (`user_id`, enums, flags, ids). Callers (routes, other services) map their inputs into that signature.
- **Rare exception:** a single typed integration document (whole external payload) may be one argument when the object is the natural atomic unit; document that in the class docstring.

## Typed errors

- Define **nested `Exception` subclasses** on the service for expected domain failures (`NotFound`, `Conflict`, etc.). Map them to HTTP or outer handling in routes/commands — do not swallow silently.

**Good:** `raise CreateFooService.AlreadyExists` from `execute`; route maps to 409.

**Bad:** `execute` returns `None` on error; generic `raise ValueError` without a stable type for the API layer.

## Events and side effects

- **Side effects that cross boundaries** (outbox, notifications, analytics) go through **dedicated ports/adapters or small event/helper services** invoked from the orchestrating service — not ad-hoc logic in routes and not duplicated across DAOs.
